```cpp
// from llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp
static Instruction *foldShuffleOfSelects(Instruction &I,
                                         const TargetTransformInfo &TTI,
                                         const DataLayout &DL) {
  auto *SVI = dyn_cast<ShuffleVectorInst>(&I);
  if (!SVI)
    return nullptr;

  Value *V1 = SVI->getOperand(0);
  Value *V2 = SVI->getOperand(1);
  auto *Sel1 = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V1);
  auto *Sel2 = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V2);
  // ...
  VectorType *SrcVTy = cast<VectorType>(V1->getType());
  // ...
  VectorType *DstVecTy = SVI->getType();
```
It seems `SrcVTy` is exactly what I need. It's defined as the type of the first operand.

So, the fix is to replace `DstVecTy` with `SrcVTy` in the `getShuffleCost` call.

The previous `sed` command was:
`sed -i "s/TTI.getShuffleCost(SK_Permute, VTy, NewMask,/TTI.getShuffleCost(SK_Permute, SrcVTy, NewMask,/" llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp`
This was wrong because the variables are `SK`, `DstVecTy`, and `Mask`.

The correct `sed` command should be:
`sed -i "s/TTI.getShuffleCost(SK, DstVecTy, Mask, CostKind, 0, nullptr,/TTI.getShuffleCost(SK, SrcVTy, Mask, CostKind, 0, nullptr,/" llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp`

Let's apply this change.

```bash
sed -i 's/OldCost += TTI.getShuffleCost(SK, DstVecTy, Mask, CostKind, 0, nullptr,/OldCost += TTI.getShuffleCost(SK, SrcVTy, Mask, CostKind, 0, nullptr,/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp
```

